<BIOGRAPHY SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="WRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Ethel Wilson : biography</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Created from original research by members of the Orlando Project</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>6 August 2010</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="PAD" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>13 August 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="PAD" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>17 August 2010</DATE><ITEM>check-in on behalf of pad</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="PAD" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>19 August 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>Doing a little bit of writing and quite enjoying it! --emh</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>8 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>Continued trucking through, figured out some new tagging practices looking at Online Documentation. Probably need some chronstructs for major life events and &quot;moves&quot; but haven&apos;t quite figured out how to do that yet or where it&apos;s needed. Tried to thoroughly go through existing entry (modifying jobs, family members, schools/orgs, etc.) until &quot;Teaching&quot; instead of writing very much new material. Happy Thanksgiving weekend.Cheers. --EMH</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>to be continued!</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>18 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>21 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>Fixed many of the bibcits, edited and added content. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>24 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>28 October 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>29 October 2010</DATE><ITEM>Hello Isobel-- I left a general note at the bottom of the entry.Going to have a look at the writing and start to transfer relevant parts over. At this point of organizing/writing, I tend to not check the entry for spelling and grammar, sadly, so please don&apos;t be too aghast at these kinds of errors...If I have provided too much detail at any point please feel free to take a knife to the entry. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>1 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="CFC" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>24 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>31 January 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>11 February 2011</DATE><ITEM>I believe this is ready to be CAS-ed. I removed some information I considered to be tangential or subjective mostly for the sake of length. I also fixed the bibcits and did a pretty good (I hope!) grammar/spelling/formatting check. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 February 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, and a rbv-c equivalent</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>9 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>10 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>13 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>30 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>Cas-ing and tag reports are done with some researchnotes remaining. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c, cft c, pilot 41</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Biography</HEADING><STANDARD>Wilson, Ethel</STANDARD><DIV1><PERSONNAME><DIV2><DATASTRUCT><DATAITEM><BIRTHNAME REG="Bryant, Ethel"><GIVEN>Ethel</GIVEN><SURNAME>Bryant</SURNAME></BIRTHNAME></DATAITEM><DATAITEM><MARRIED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Wilson, Ethel">Wilson</MARRIED></DATAITEM></DATASTRUCT></DIV2></PERSONNAME></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Birth and Family</HEADING><BIRTH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="SYS"><DATE>20 January 1888</DATE><CHRONPROSE>Ethel Bryant (later EW) was born in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Port Elizabeth</SETTLEMENT>, <GEOG>South Africa</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Wesleyan Methodist</ORGNAME> missionary parents. <BIRTHPOSITION POSITION="ONLY">She was their only surviving child.</BIRTHPOSITION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 3, 8" DBREF="64285">3, 8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></BIRTH></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><GEOGHERITAGE>Born in <PLACE><GEOG>South Africa</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE></GEOGHERITAGE> to <RACECOLOUR REG="white">white</RACECOLOUR> parents of <NATIONALHERITAGE SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">British</NATIONALHERITAGE> origin but later settled in <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Canadian">Canada</NATIONALITY>, and accustomed in later years to a high <CLASS SOCIALRANK="PROFESSIONAL" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">professional</CLASS> standard of living, EW had a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church"><DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Methodist">Methodist</DENOMINATION></ORGNAME>, <CLASS SOCIALRANK="ENTREPRENEURIAL-INDUSTRIALIST" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">comfortable</CLASS>, sheltered upbringing that greatly affected her outlook. She later said: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">It was not until I married that I learned it was possible to enjoy life without first passing a moral judgment on it.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 1-2" DBREF="64825">1-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Mother</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s mother was <NAME STANDARD="Bryant, Eliza Davis Malkin">Eliza Davis Malkin</NAME>, called <SOCALLED>Lila</SOCALLED>. She was the oldest of nine children born to a serious, deeply pious <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Wesleyan Methodist</ORGNAME> family at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Burslem</SETTLEMENT> in <REGION CURRENT="West Midlands" REG="Staffordshire">Staffordshire</REGION>, <GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>. Upon marriage, she became a <JOB REG="minister (of religion)">missionary</JOB> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Port Elizabeth</SETTLEMENT>, <GEOG>South Africa</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>. She died on <DATE>28 July 1889</DATE>, when EW was eighteen months old, following the birth of her second child, a son, who also died ten days later.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 5, 7, 8" DBREF="64285">5, 7, 8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="GRANDMOTHER"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME>Annie Malkin</NAME>, EW&apos;s maternal grandmother, was important at a later stage of her upbringing.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><HEADING>Father</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s father was <NAME>Robert Bryant</NAME>. Eleven years before moving to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Port Elizabeth</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="South Africa"></GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>, he had come to South Africa at the age of twenty after being diagnosed with a dormant form of tuberculosis. He returned to England to marry; then, three weeks after his wedding to Lila, he was back in South Africa as a <JOB REG="minister (of religion)">missionary</JOB>. Later, in Britain, he <JOB CURRENTALTERNATIVETERM="clergyman" REG="minister (of religion)">held parishes</JOB> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Pembroke</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Pembrokeshire"></REGION> in <GEOG>Wales</GEOG></PLACE>, as well as <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Brighton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Sussex"></REGION> on the south coast of <GEOG REG="England">England</GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="London">Acton</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> near London.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 6, 7, 9, 12" DBREF="64285">6, 7, 9, 12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE>19 June 1897</DATE><CHRONPROSE>At age forty her father, <NAME>Robert Bryant</NAME>, died of pneumonia, leaving Ethel Bryant (later EW) an orphan. She was then aged nine.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 12" DBREF="64285">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></DIV2></MEMBER><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s parents were married by <NAME>Frederic William Macdonald</NAME>, an uncle of <NAME>Rudyard Kipling</NAME>, brother of writer <NAME>Louisa Baldwin</NAME>, and brother-in-law of painter <NAME STANDARD="Burne-Jones, Sir Edward Coley">Edward Burne-Jones</NAME>. As a wedding gift, Macdonald gave Lila and Robert drawings by Burne-Jones which Ethel Wilson eventually donated to the <ORGNAME>Art Gallery of Victoria</ORGNAME>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 6" DBREF="64285">6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><MEMBER RELATION="FATHER"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW would remember fondly the time she spent with her father in England when <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">life was luminous and merry and beloved.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 9-10" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">9-10</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Unusually, he did not remarry. Although he died when EW was only nine, she remembered him for his <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sense of joy and fun and humour that fed and lightened [his wife], and brightened young and old people.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 11" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MIGRATED"><DIV2><HEADING>Return to England</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>After his wife&apos;s death, EW&apos;s father was implored to return to <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> with Ethel, but he lingered for one year. She was two and a half when father and daughter left <PLACE><GEOG>South Africa</GEOG><AREA REG="Africa"></AREA></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 9" DBREF="64285">9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW lived with a series of aunts and uncles in <PLACE><REGION CURRENT="West Midlands" REG="Staffordshire">Staffordshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> after her father died.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 12" DBREF="64285">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Coming to Canada</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MIGRATED"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1898-06-" CERTAINTY="C">Summer 1898</DATE><CHRONPROSE>A year after EW&apos;s father died, her maternal grandmother, <NAME>Annie Malkin</NAME>, took Ethel from <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> to her home in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, where she was then raised by the extended Malkin family.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 13" DBREF="64285">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>In Vancouver, the Malkins ran a premier grocery business. EW was lucky in that she was lovingly cared for by her extended family, living a life of relative ease and comfort. However, she was bereft of the intimate ties of her childhood as her new family members were still unfamiliar and strange. </P><P>EW lived with her grandmother and two unmarried aunts, all with deep <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Wesleyan</ORGNAME> faith, for twenty-one years until Annie Malkin&apos;s death in <DATE VALUE="1919--">1919</DATE>. EW later regarded her Methodist upbringing as restricted and blinkered, yet at the same time she valued the unwavering faith and steadfastness of her grandmother, later viewing her as a source of stability for an insecure and unsure child.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 13, 20, 27" DBREF="64285">13, 20, 27</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Education</HEADING><EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1898-09-" CERTAINTY="C">Fall 1898</DATE><CHRONPROSE>The ten-year-old Ethel Bryant (later EW) was enrolled in Miss <INSTRUCTOR><NAME>Jessie Gordon</NAME></INSTRUCTOR>&apos;s <ORGNAME STANDARD="Anglican Church">Anglican</ORGNAME> school for girls, <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="DAYSCHOOL" STUDENTBODY="SINGLESEX" RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="PRIMARY" REG="Crofton House"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Crofton House">Crofton House</ORGNAME></SCHOOL> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 19" DBREF="64285">19</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>At Crofton House she heard <TEXT><NAME>Pauline Johnson</NAME>, the Mohawk poet from <PLACE><REGION>Ontario</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, orate</TEXT>, but she was too shy to speak to or visit her. Despite her shyness, Ethel excelled at Crofton House.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 27, 29" DBREF="64285">27, 29</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Education in England</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>As a teenager EW was sent back to England for further education at <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="BOARDING" STUDENTBODY="SINGLESEX" RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="SECONDARY" REG="Trinity Hall School"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Trinity Hall School,, Southport">Trinity Hall School</ORGNAME></SCHOOL> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Southport</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>Lancashire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Wesleyan Methodist</ORGNAME> boarding school for girls. She later recalled this as a highly regimented, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">rigorous, almost spartan</QUOTE> experience which nevertheless provided her with excellent material for her fiction. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 32, 33" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">32, 33</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Painfully shy, in her first year she spent most of her time in the library. In her second year she earned the admiration of her peers through athletic achievement. She continued to excel academically and her headmaster and schoolmates would remember her twenty-five years later as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the School Beauty.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 40" DBREF="64285">40</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>Nonetheless, EW at this time acquired a reputation for great humility which she maintained throughout her life.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 40" DBREF="64285">40</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Later, back in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG>Canada</GEOG></PLACE>, she trained as a teacher at the <ORGNAME>Vancouver Normal School</ORGNAME> from <DATE VALUE="1906-09-" CERTAINTY="AFTER">September, 1906</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 44-45" DBREF="64285">44-45</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Extended Family</HEADING><FAMILY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>During her time in England, EW renewed contact with the extended family of both her mother and her father. She spent her first summer in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Burslem</SETTLEMENT><REGION CURRENT="West Midlands" REG="Staffordshire"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> with her Aunt <NAME STANDARD="Malkin, Edith">Edith</NAME> and Uncle <NAME>Sydney Malkin</NAME>, although she did not much enjoy her time there. Sydney Malkin was a lay minister who also ran unsuccessfully for office as mayor and as Liberal member of parliament. (He did become mayor later on.) Ethel sensed a cold superiority as well as hypocrisy in the apparent charity and piety of her aunt and uncle.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 34, 35" DBREF="64285">34, 35</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>During the second summer which she spent back in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> from <PLACE><GEOG>Canada</GEOG></PLACE>, EW also had the opportunity to visit <PLACE><GEOG>France.</GEOG></PLACE>. She returned from England to Canada in 1906. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 38, 41" DBREF="64285">38, 41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>A childless great-aunt and great-uncle, <NAME STANDARD="Edge, Annie">Annie</NAME> and <NAME>John Edge</NAME>, funded this trip to <PLACE><GEOG>France</GEOG></PLACE>, on which EW was accompanied by Aunt Edith and Uncle Sydney. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 38" DBREF="64285">38</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><MEMBER RELATION="AUNT"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>While she had mixed feelings for the relatives on her mother&apos;s side, EW greatly enjoyed her father&apos;s side of the family. His half-sister <NAME>Margaret Bryant</NAME> was a respected <JOB REG="journalist">journalist</JOB> for <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Observer</TITLE> and although her writing was not always signed, she contributed significantly to the famous 1911 edition of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Encyclopaedia Britannica</TITLE>.<SCHOLARNOTE><P>She seems to have provided sections of entries on classical, medieval, French and English literary, and French historical topics, as the encyclopaedia&apos;s online archive records.</P></SCHOLARNOTE>She also belonged to the <ORGNAME>Royal Institute of International Affairs</ORGNAME> and the <ORGNAME>League of Nations</ORGNAME>.</P><P>An older half-sister of EW&apos;s father, <NAME>Hannah Waller Atkinson</NAME>, was equally accomplished, having lived for a time in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>St Petersburg</SETTLEMENT><GEOG CURRENT="Russian Federation" REG="Russia"></GEOG> with the pianist at the <PLACENAME>Imperial Palace</PLACENAME></PLACE>. She would eventually <JOB REG="translator">translate</JOB> <NAME STANDARD="Pushkin, Alexander Sergeevich">Pushkin</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Tale of the Golden Cockerel</TITLE> into English. However, she was primarily a <JOB REG="music">musician</JOB> and was <NAME>Clara Schumann</NAME>&apos;s last pupil in <PLACE><GEOG>Germany</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 35-36" DBREF="64285">35-36</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>These women of charm and accomplishment greatly enriched EW&apos;s imagination. They introduced her to the pleasures of cultural life in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>, taking her to concerts, art galleries, theatres and restaurants. She would go on to write about her father&apos;s sisters in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Reflections in a Pool</TITLE>, saying she admired them <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">for their unshockability and funniness and cleverness and musicalness.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 36" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">36</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Visits with the Bryant sisters were not approved of by the Malkin side of the family; the sisters had encouraged EW to become an actress (likely prompted by her beauty and artistic sensibiltity), a course the Malkins would have abhorred.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 36, 42" DBREF="64285">36, 42</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Return to Canada and Teaching</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>When she returned to Canada in <DATE>1906</DATE>, EW was not formally introduced into society through a coming-out party, unlike many girls returning from boarding school at age eighteen. Instead, she set about earning a living and was admitted to a teacher training program at the <ORGNAME>Vancouver Normal School</ORGNAME> in <DATE VALUE="1906-09-">September, 1906</DATE>. She subsequently <JOB REG="teacher">taught</JOB> in four different public elementary schools over the next thirteen years. <REMUNERATION>In the public city system she was paid $47.50 per month.</REMUNERATION> When asked later if she enjoyed her work as a teacher with children, EW seemed annoyed by the question and abruptly replied, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">No</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 44-6" DBREF="64285">44-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> However, pupils interviewed years later indicated that she communicated neither negativity nor dissatisfaction in the classroom. She was remembered as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">beautiful and gentle. She never disciplined or teased anyone. We all loved her.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 46" DBREF="64285">46</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Between <DATERANGE FROM="1918-10-18" TO="1919-11-19" EXACT="BOTH">18 October 1918 and 19 November 1919</DATERANGE> schools in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> were closed over the worst wave of the outbreak of the Spanish Influenza there. The school where EW was teaching at this time, <ORGNAME STANDARD="Dawson Elementary School">Dawson Elementary</ORGNAME>, was turned into a temporary hospital and cots replaced the desks. Because of the war, doctors and nurses were badly needed and EW <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="nurse">volunteered</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> for the tasks of disinfecting the school and helping keep patients comfortable. However, she soon became ill herself.</P><P>Ethel Bryant resigned from the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME>Vancouver School Board</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> on <DATE>26 July 1920</DATE>, roughly five months before her wedding.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 59, 66" DBREF="64285">59, 66</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>However, the bout of Spanish flu she contracted as a teacher had permanent effects. For the rest of her life EW remained susceptible to anaemia. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 59" DBREF="64285">59</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS EROTIC="EROTICNO"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In <DATE VALUE="1912--" CERTAINTY="ROUGHLYDATED">1912</DATE> EW was briefly engaged to a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Methodist</ORGNAME> lawyer, <NAME>John Pethybridge Nicolls</NAME>, whose family was close with her grandmother. She had known him since she was a young teenager; he was almost twenty years older than she was. Their courtship took place primarily in public through family gatherings and their church. Invitations to the wedding were sent out and presents began to arrive, but EW&apos;s doubts about the match increased and she broke off the engagement. The affair was a source of great personal embarassment for her.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 51, 54-5" DBREF="64285">51, 54-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>There are no clear records of the date of EW&apos;s engagement. Biographer <NAME>David Stouck</NAME> infers that it occurred in 1912 from the fact that EW was not teaching at this time.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 55" DBREF="64285">55</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></INTIMATERELATIONSHIPS></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Until the age of thirty-one EW continued to live with her grandmother <NAME>Annie Malkin</NAME> and two elderly aunts. The household was severe for a young woman: on Sundays, Annie Malkin&apos;s strict <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Methodist</ORGNAME> sensibilities led her to forbid <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>cooking</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>knitting</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>, newspaper reading, or laughter, and to permit only hymns and classical music to be played on the gramophone. EW had a reputation as a grand <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>storyteller</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> for many young cousins. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 49-50" DBREF="64285">49-50</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Towards Independence</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Having lived until the age of thirty-one with her elderly relations on <PLACE><ADDRESS REG="Barclay Street"><ADDRLINE>Barclay Street at Jervis</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, EW moved after the death of her grandmother in <DATE VALUE="1919-03-17">1919</DATE>, to live at the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Langham Hotel</PLACENAME> in <SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>. While discussing some of the humbler characters in her stories, she made the one and only direct reference to this time. She explained that during her time living in a boarding house she had observed women who had to endure great loneliness while also working to earn a living. She stated, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I feel terrific sympathy for anyone who must stand alone and work out their salvation.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 62" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">62</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> However, it cannot be said with certainty that EW herself experienced loneliness during this time. Other boarders at the Langham Hotel remember her as popular and as receiving many callers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 61-2" DBREF="64285">61-62</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><CULTURALFORMATION><RELIGION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P> While EW&apos;s younger cousins had thought her family home was an impossible environment for a young woman, it is unclear that she was unhappy and it is unlikely that she rebelled. Thus, although EW&apos;s new life at the Langham Hotel freed her from severe <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Methodist</ORGNAME> prohibitions, she would nonetheless later say, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I am proud of my strict upbringing because as long as one feels loved, a conventional home life is salutary, gives assurance. And then one can always move outwards from it!</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 50" DBREF="64285">50</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 211" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">211</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></RELIGION></CULTURALFORMATION></DIV1><DIV1><EDUCATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P><KEYWORDCLASS KEYWORDTYPE="creative activity">painting</KEYWORDCLASS>EW was interested in <SUBJECT>drawing</SUBJECT> and <SUBJECT>painting</SUBJECT> throughout her youth. She sought out painting lessons in her young adulthood through <INSTRUCTOR><NAME>Emily Carr</NAME></INSTRUCTOR>, who lived in Vancouver between <DATERANGE FROM="1906--" TO="1910--" EXACT="BOTH">1906 and 1910</DATERANGE>. However, when the private lessons turned out to consist <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">entirely of conversation,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 53" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">53</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EW abandoned them, primarily for financial reasons.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 53" DBREF="64285">53</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></EDUCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Marriage</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><MARRIAGE><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE>4 January 1921</DATE><CHRONPROSE><NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Ethel">Ethel Bryant</NAME> married <JOB REG="physician">Dr </JOB><NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Wallace">Wallace Algernon Wilson</NAME>, at a quiet ceremony at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Wesley Methodist Church</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 67-8" DBREF="64885">67-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P> It is not certain when she met Wallace Wilson. She indicated they met before the war in London, probably during a visit in the <DATE VALUE="1913-04-" CERTAINTY="C">spring of 1913</DATE>. It is known that they began to spend more time together after Ethel moved to the Langham Hotel. They shared numerous athletic and intellectual interests and often exchanged books and read aloud to one another. Wallace proposed in early <DATE VALUE="1920-06-" CERTAINTY="C">summer 1920</DATE>. Their marriage has been described as an extraordinarily perfect union; EW later wote to a friend <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">it has been wonderful for us . . . beyond imagination.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 63, 65-6" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">63, 65-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MARRIAGE></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="VISITED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Their delayed honeymoon to <PLACE><PLACENAME CURRENT="Lac Le Jeune">Fish Lake</PLACENAME><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> (later renamed Lac Le Jeune), high in the hills south of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Kamloops</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, was the glorious start of annual fishing trips to this spot, which appears as Three Loon Lake in EW&apos;s novel <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 68-70" DBREF="64285">68-70</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Initially the newlyweds lived with Wallace&apos;s mother, with whom EW had an uneasy relationship. This made the early years of the marriage somewhat difficult. <CHILDLESSNESS>This difficulty and tension may have been exacerbated by the fact that the marriage was childless.</CHILDLESSNESS> The Wilsons did not speak openly about their lack of children, but many who knew them guessed that it was not by choice.</P><P>Married life became easier when EW&apos;s mother-in-law moved out to live with her daughter in 1927. The following year, Wallace Wilson was elected president of the <ORGNAME>British Columbia Medical Association</ORGNAME>. With the position, EW&apos;s social obligations became quite significant as she was required to host and attend countless teas, dinners, and cocktail parties.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Wallace served as President of the <ORGNAME>Canadian Medical Association</ORGNAME> from 1946 to 1947<RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: the dates for this are not included in the source.</RESEARCHNOTE> and he retired from practice in 1953. He would go on to lecture on medical ethics at the <ORGNAME>University of British Columbia</ORGNAME>. He was also a founding member of the <ORGNAME>B. C. Cancer Foundation</ORGNAME> and the <ORGNAME>Narcotics Association of Vancouver</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 71, 73-4, 178" DBREF="64285">71, 73-4, 178</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In the course of her social duties EW would meet <NAME STANDARD="Rothschild, James de">Baron de Rothschild</NAME>, <NAME>Sir Robert Ouvry</NAME>, and the German financier and Westerm pro-<ORGNAME STANDARD="Nazis">Nazi</ORGNAME> organizer <NAME STANDARD="Heydebreck, Hans-Adam Otto von">Baron von Heydebreck (known as Peter)</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 73-4" DBREF="64285">73-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Travel Abroad</HEADING><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW accompanied her husband to Europe while he completed postgraduate work in internal medicine in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vienna</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Austria"></GEOG></PLACE> <DATERANGE FROM="1928--" TO="1929--" EXACT="BOTH">from 1928 to 1929</DATERANGE>. In the <DATE VALUE="1930-03-" CERTAINTY="C">spring of 1930</DATE>, the couple went on a cruise through the <PLACE><REGION REG="Mediterranean Sea">Mediterranean</REGION></PLACE>, visiting <PLACE><REGION>Gibraltar</REGION></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG CURRENT="Israel" REG="Israel">Palestine</GEOG></PLACE>, <PLACE><GEOG REG="Egypt">Egypt</GEOG> (which she used in a short story about a couple visiting the <PLACENAME>Valley of the Kings</PLACENAME></PLACE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Haply the Soul of My Grandmother</TITLE>), <PLACE><GEOG REG="Algeria">Algeria</GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><GEOG REG="Greece">Greece</GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 74-6" DBREF="64285">74-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Return to Vancouver</HEADING><WEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1931, <NAME>Wallace Wilson</NAME> was admitted as a Fellow of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royal College of Surgeons">Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons</ORGNAME>. His practice was now located on <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>West Georgia Street</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, a desirable area of <SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>. In a difficult economic time, the Wilsons lived quite comfortably. They had a cook and a gardener, travelled frequently, and owned their house in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Shaughnessy</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, where they lived until 1943.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 81" DBREF="64285">81</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></WEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><LEISUREANDSOCIETY><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW spent some of her time playing tennis, swimming and horseback riding, while also attending to her social duties as wife of a successful doctor. Although Wallace Wilson was well-liked by almost everyone who knew him, people sometimes found EW&apos;s manner somewhat cool and off-putting. Biographers such as <NAME>David Stouck</NAME> attribute this to a mature manifestation of her early shyness and insecurity. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 82, 85" DBREF="64285">82, 85</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LEISUREANDSOCIETY></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>It was during the 1930s that EW began to <JOB REG="writer">write</JOB>; however, she was extremely private to the point of being secretive about her writing.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>The Wilsons travelled again to Europe in the summer of 1938. Upon arriving in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> on <DATE VALUE="1938-07-05">5 July 1938</DATE> EW was particularly excited to see her half-aunts the Bryant sisters again. By this time it had been revealed that <NAME>Margaret Bryant</NAME> had hoped to be the one to raise EW, but that she was deemed to be not religious enough for the family to agree. At a gathering at Margaret Bryant&apos;s in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="London">St Pancras</SETTLEMENT> immediately after attending a cricket match at <PLACENAME REG="Lords Cricket Ground">Lords</PLACENAME><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> with wealthy friends from Vancouver, EW was struck by the humble material surroundings of her aunts&apos; artistic and intellectual friends. She wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I got very depressed as I thought how much more of London lives at the St Pancras level. Hundreds live at Lords level, thousands perhaps, but thousands or millions below that level.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 90" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">90</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> During this visit to London EW visited the house where <NAME STANDARD="Keats, John">Keats</NAME> once lived. On this same trip, the Wilsons also travelled to<PLACE><GEOG>Scandinavia</GEOG></PLACE> and the <PLACE><GEOG>Netherlands</GEOG></PLACE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 89, 92, 95" DBREF="64285">89, 92, 95</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>World War II</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>During the Second World War, EW famously said that she forgot her <JOB REG="writer">writing</JOB> to help in the war effort. Although she did indeed publish two stories during the war, she also <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES" REG="Red Cross aide">volunteered</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> for the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="Canadian Red Cross">Red Cross</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, packing boxes and rolling bandages to be sent to forces in Europe and also <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="editor">editing</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver Calling</TITLE>, a bi-monthly bulletin, and writing a handbook for the Red Cross. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 98, 102-3" DBREF="64285">98, 102-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>From <DATERANGE FROM="1941--" TO="1943--" EXACT="BOTH">1941 to 1943</DATERANGE>, the Wilsons received into their home sixteen-year-old <NAME>Audrey Butler</NAME>, an evacuee from England. They were generous with both their familial warmth and finances. Audrey shared the Wilsons&apos; love of <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME> and the outdoors. In 1942 she finished high school and briefly enrolled at <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME> before she joined the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royal Canadian Naval Service">Women&apos;s Royal Canadian Naval Service </ORGNAME> in 1943. She was eventually sent overseas.<SCHOLARNOTE><P>This force shared with its British counterpart, the <ORGNAME>Women&apos;s Royal Navy Service</ORGNAME>, the nickname WRNS or Wrens.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></P><P>Audrey returned to the Wilsons in 1947 and they welcomed her back. She later said she felt pressure from EW to choose between her natural parents and the Wilsons.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 103-4, 139" DBREF="64285">103-4, 139</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 113-4" DBREF="64885">113-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The Wilsons again reunited with Audrey in the <DATE VALUE="1956-04-" CERTAINTY="C">spring of 1956</DATE> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Amsterdam</SETTLEMENT><GEOG REG="Netherlands"></GEOG></PLACE>. After this meeting EW wrote to John Gray: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">What a lovely young woman she has become, &amp; sometimes her beauty shines like a star. She is so companionable, &amp; we never laughed so much together.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 216-7" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">216-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1942 <NAME>Wallace Wilson</NAME> <JOB REG="army officer">joined the army</JOB> again. He had previously served in 1915 at a base for Allied operations in <PLACE><GEOG>Greece</GEOG></PLACE> as a member of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Royal Canadian Army Medical Corps">Royal Canadian Medical Corps</ORGNAME>. As a part of his duties in World War Two he did tours of duty in eastern Canada and England.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 105" DBREF="64285">105</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1943 the Wilsons moved to a third-floor apartment in <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Kensington Place</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, at the corner of <ADDRESS REG="Nicola Street"><ADDRLINE>Nicola Street and Beach Avenue</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS>, <SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, where they lived until 1965.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 105" DBREF="64285">105</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Post-War</HEADING><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In <DATE>1947</DATE>, <NAME>Wallace Wilson</NAME> fell ill with what doctors believed to be a severe form of dermatitis or eczema. For eighteen months he was seriously ill. He lost his hair and his entire body was inflamed. EW was required, on doctors&apos; orders, to take a holiday away from Wallace for a month in the summer of <DATE VALUE="1948-07-" CERTAINTY="C">1948</DATE>. Wallace&apos;s condition was not well understood by doctors, who believed it to be stress-induced.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpline 142" DBREF="64885">142</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 140-1" DBREF="64285">140-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="MENTAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Some doctors described EW as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hovering</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">too intense</QUOTE>, while some of her friends remembered her in an almost hysterical state, and commented in interviews upon the perceived unnatural or pathological dependency EW had on her husband. Such perceptions may reveal more about attitudes towards women at the time than facts about EW.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 141" DBREF="64285">141</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 142" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">142</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Wallace&apos;s condition did not improve in the hospital and in <DATE VALUE="1948-11-">November 1948</DATE> he returned home, where EW managed his care, overseeing two nurses in addition to her housekeeper. He lapsed in and out of severe illness until the <DATE VALUE="1949-10-" CERTAINTY="C">fall of 1949</DATE>. Curiously, his health significantly improved when doctors completely stopped prescribing antibiotics.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 141, 142" DBREF="64285">141-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="MENTAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Wallace&apos;s illness likely reawakened EW&apos;s earlier experience of intimate loss. Her work from this time focuses sharply on the trauma of loss, particularly through accidents, long-term separation, and sudden death.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 141, 142" DBREF="64285">141-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Vancouver Writing Group</HEADING><OCCUPATION><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1949--">1949</DATE><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: the source details her joining of a writer&apos;s committee to make a report on the state of the arts in Canada (1949) and her joining a writing group around 1950. This section appears to be referring to the committee but it is a little confusing. img: I revised this chronprose to reflect what Kate says, since it also agrees with the shortprose, but it really needs ok-ing by Emily in its new form.</RESEARCHNOTE><CHRONPROSE>Although reluctant to support official Canadian literary organizations, EW joined a committee formed to <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="literary critic">express its views</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> on the state of literature in Canada. The following year she became a member of a <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="writing-group member">writing group</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 162-3" DBREF="64285">162-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The early 1950s were a pleasurable time for EW, who enjoyed creative success in addition to the improved health of her husband. Furthermore, she now became more active in the Canadian literary scene. Since the beginning of her <JOB REG="writer">publishing career</JOB> she had been extremely reluctant to participate in literary organizations in a sustained way. In <DATE VALUE="1947--">1947</DATE>, <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME>, critic of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE>, invited her to join the <ORGNAME>Canadian Authors Association</ORGNAME> but she declined. Then in 1949 <NAME>Dorothy Livesay</NAME> convinced her to join the <ORGNAME>Royal Commission on National Development in the Arts, Letters and Sciences</ORGNAME>, a public agency reporting on the state of the arts in Canada. For two years the agency advocated for necessity of legally recognizing that Canadian culture needed to be promoted and protected. However, EW only <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="committee woman">committed her name and finances</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY>; she did not participate in the actual writing of the report. Finally in 1950 <NAME>Earle Birney</NAME> succeeded in persuading her to meet with a local writing group that was the non-academic extension of a creative writing course Birney taught at <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME>. The group invited writers with publishing success to attend, including <NAME>Robert Harlow</NAME>, <NAME>Dorothy Livesay</NAME>, <NAME>Eric Nicol</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="McConnell, William">William</NAME> and <NAME>Alice McConnell</NAME>, <NAME>Mario Prizek</NAME> and <NAME>Ernest Perrault</NAME>. EW participated in the group&apos;s monthly meetings for roughly five years and she <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="literary hostess">hosted the meetings</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> at her apartment at Kensington Place.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 162-3" DBREF="64285">162-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Of EW as a hostess Bob Patchell stated: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">She could strike terror. . . into the hearts of people who were <SOCALLED>not properly brought up.</SOCALLED> When we walked in the door we were trying to be Edwardian gentlemen and trying at least to keep the language of our criticism to polite English rather than the usual Anglo-Saxonisms that most of the time we hurled at each other about our literary efforts.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 154" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">154</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>The Informal Critic</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>Despite her formidable commitment to propriety, EW was remembered as an exceptionally gracious <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="hostess">host</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> with an impeccably tasteful home. From the art on the walls to the furniture, each object there had special significance; many of them were inherited through the family or acquired through the Wilsons&apos; travels. Among the writers in the group, EW was impressed by the work of <NAME>Mario Prizek</NAME>. Although she found his writing strange to her sensibility, she nevertheless deemed it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">near genius</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 166" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">166</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also said <NAME>Ernest Perrault</NAME>&apos;s stories were <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">completely natural</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">masterly</QUOTE>, and she found <NAME>Eric Nicol</NAME>&apos;s work to be tough, funny and clever. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 163, 166, 167" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">163, 166, 167</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 154" DBREF="64885">154</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW&apos;s refined taste, propriety and <POLITICALAFFILIATION MEMBERSHIP="MEMBERSHIPYES" REG="Conservative">conservative</POLITICALAFFILIATION> political sensibility led to some conflict with <NAME>Earle Birney</NAME>. His approach to poetry and art was political, but often socialist. EW was uncomfortable with what she saw as his black-and-white approach to the topic of wealth distribution and morality. The rich and elite were not always, she felt, greedy and exploitatitive. In response to his poem <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Damnation of Vancouver</TITLE>, she complicated this binary, citing the common good that many wealthy individuals in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> strove towards, particularly as patrons of the arts. Specifically, she invoked her uncle <NAME>Harold Malkin</NAME>, who donated the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Marion Malkin Memorial Bowl">Malkin Bowl</ORGNAME> theatre in memory of his wife, while also reminding Birney of the countless anonymous philanthropic works of wealthy individuals.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 164-5" DBREF="64285">164-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Literary Friends and Acquaintances</HEADING><FRIENDSASSOCIATES><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>EW remained friends with <NAME>Dorothy Livesay</NAME> through the Vancouver writers&apos; group. Livesay wrote a profile on Wilson in <DATE VALUE="1952--">1952</DATE> with the intent to promote <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>. Wilson proposed various corrections for the article. In particular she took issue with the way Livesay claimed that her somewhat severe and conventional upbringing had made her self-assured. Wilson preferred to say it had given her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a sense of proportion</QUOTE>, but Livesay did not change her phrasing.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 173-4" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">173-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The relations between the two women were occasionally stiff, but Livesay remained enthusiastic about Wilson&apos;s work in general and Wilson admired Livesay&apos;s commitment to the arts.</P><P>Through parties hosted by her eventual publisher, the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan Company</ORGNAME>, EW also met <NAME>Morley Callaghan</NAME>, who admired her writing. Other writers she knew included <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>, <NAME>A. J. M. Smith</NAME>, <NAME>Robert Weaver</NAME>, <ORGNAME>Group of Seven</ORGNAME> painter <NAME>Lawren Harris</NAME>, and <NAME>Dylan Thomas</NAME>. She became good friends with <NAME STANDARD="De la Roche, Mazo">Mazo de la Roche</NAME>, a Canadian best-selling author, but their appreciation for one another was not literary. By 1955 De la Roche had still read nothing of EW&apos;s work. For her part, EW time and again withheld her opinion on the quality of De la Roche&apos;s books. There is no record of any opinion Wilson might have had about De la Roche&apos;s lifelong companionship with her cousin <NAME>Carolyn Clement</NAME>. However, shortly after the publication of <NAME>Jane Rule</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Desert of the Heart</TITLE>, a pioneer text in queer literature, EW entertained Rule and her companion <NAME>Helen Sonthoff</NAME>. The only record of her thoughts on homosexuality is very discreet and concerns her encounter with English novelist <NAME>Angus Wilson</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 174-177" DBREF="64285">174-177</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In a letter EW wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I have always understood that he has a characteristic common to many bachelor artists &amp; writers, but of course I do not know. Even if so, that does not prevent him from being a very interesting person to talk to.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 175" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">175</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In 1960 EW began a long correspondence with <NAME>Margaret Laurence</NAME> that lasted until her own death. Laurence, as an emerging writer, immensely valued the friendship, and wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I was starved for the company of other writers, and here was an older woman whose work I admired so much, taking the time to talk with and encourage a young and unknown writer.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 246-7" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">246-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The friendship testifies to the fact that although EW did not believe in the value of systematized creative writing classes, she nevertheless thought personal mentorship to be valuable in the development of a writer. Wilson reserved her highest praise for Laurence until the <DATE VALUE="1964-04-" CERTAINTY="C">spring of 1964</DATE>, when she received a copy of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Stone Angel</TITLE>. She wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Dear Margaret what a darling you are to send me the <EMPH>glorious</EMPH> book. . . . I simply can&apos;t say all I feel . . . . To me, this is a <EMPH>great</EMPH> book. I believe some people could not read it, because it is the very life of life, and they do not know life. . . . It has a splendour . . . the night in the cannery is terrific.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 270" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">270</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Her enthusiasm for the book led her to offer a few lines of praise to be used as advertising, which was a first for her.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 243, 270" DBREF="64285">243, 270</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></FRIENDSASSOCIATES></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Later Years</HEADING><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1950--" CERTAINTY="AFTER">1950</DATE><CHRONPROSE>From about this year until the mid-1950s, EW and her <NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Wallace">husband</NAME> faced renewed health problems.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 180, 208, 215-6" DBREF="64285">180, 208, 215-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>EW had developed acute arthritis in her hip. She believed the problem to have originated from a fall in the late 1940s. She underwent cortisone treatment in <DATE VALUE="1951-02-">February, 1951</DATE>, but the relief was only temporary. She spent most of the rest of her life on pain medication and almost always appeared in a wheelchair in public. Of her health EW would write, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I hate the fatigue &amp; pain of this arthritis which is so <EMPH>preventing</EMPH>, so limiting &amp; exacting.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 179,180" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">179,180</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> After reading positive reviews of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> she would also write in a letter to John Gray: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">What&apos;s an aching bone, nothing to this interesting life.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 180" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">180</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>EW underwent mastectomy for a lump in her breast on <DATE VALUE="1956-01-29">January 29, 1956</DATE>. She reported to John Gray two weeks later that the tumour had been benign; however, she recovered from surgery more slowly than expected. At this point, she stopped attending the writing group sessions. In 1958, the Wilsons both turned seventy. EW was confined to a wheelchair for venturing outside her home and was prone to deafness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 215-16, 245" DBREF="64285">215-6, 245</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>After a few years of improved health, in <DATE VALUE="1954-10-" CERTAINTY="C">mid-October of 1954</DATE> <NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Wallace">Wallace</NAME> suffered a heart attack and spent several weeks in intensive care. EW acknowledged the need to limit their social engagements at this time, but once again some friends observed her to be too protective of Wallace.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 208" DBREF="64285">208</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> His problems with his heart recurred in 1958 and he also experienced a series of serious prostate gland infections which led to five operations.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 245" DBREF="64285">245</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Although England was always held dear by EW, she was profoundly disturbed by the Suez Crisis which began in <DATE VALUE="1956-10-29" CERTAINTY="AFTER">late October, 1956</DATE>. She wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I have never been so unhappy about world and national affairs in my life&mdash;because always, before, whatever the anxieties &amp; blows, I always felt that Britain was <EMPH>right</EMPH>, &amp; this time I was, &amp; am, shocked beyond measure. I feel I never knew what <SOCALLED>shock</SOCALLED> was before, that the U.K. (with France! indeed) would land troops without notice &amp; call it <SOCALLED>Police Action.</SOCALLED><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 173" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">173</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></QUOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><OCCUPATION><DIV2><HEADING>Public Speaking</HEADING><SHORTPROSE><P>EW began a series of <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY REG="lecturer">public speaking engagements</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> the day before her mastectomy on <DATE VALUE="1956-01-28">January 28, 1956</DATE>, at the <ORGNAME>University of British Columbia</ORGNAME>, with <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">How Does a Writer Reach His Audience?</TITLE> She continued to give talks over the next nine years.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></OCCUPATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Final Years</HEADING><HEALTH><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In 1960, Wallace suffered another mild heart attack and the Wilsons became increasingly private. When they did appear in public EW was quiet and her manner was occasionally interpreted as <SOCALLED>superior</SOCALLED>; however, her perceived aloofness was likely due to her pain and deafness. She was perhaps unfairly labelled a <SOCALLED>grande dame</SOCALLED> by <NAME>Sally Creighton</NAME> in <DATE VALUE="1967--">1967</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 257-8" DBREF="64285">257-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In <DATE VALUE="1964--">1964</DATE> both Ethel and Wallace suffered falls on the steps of their building, which were unsafe in bad weather.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 204" DBREF="64885">204</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Since their apartment building at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Kensington Place</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> had caused these falls, they decided to make another move, to a bright apartment on <PLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Point Grey Road</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 204" DBREF="64885">204</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><POLITICS><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>In her later years, EW became more critical in her letters regarding social and political issues. She increasingly valorized individuals like <NAME STANDARD="De la Roche, Mazo">Mazo de La Roche</NAME> (for being a self-taught writer), as well as <NAME>Arthur Erickson</NAME> and <NAME>Northrop Frye</NAME>, for achieving distinction without doctoral degrees. Some perceived her as somewhat of a curmudgeon. She wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I reproach myself that now, in age, I permit myself to dislike the company of some people . . . . One would feed &amp; clothe them if needed &amp; possible, &amp; <SOCALLED>love</SOCALLED> in the Christian meaning of the term; but <SOCALLED>liking</SOCALLED> is different.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 262, 263" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">262, 263</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>EW was also explicitly <POLITICALAFFILIATION INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTYES" REG="anti-American">anti-American</POLITICALAFFILIATION> in her letters. She decried <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME>&apos;s decision to hire numerous American professors, expressing her distaste at listening to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an American lecturer . . . with two American degrees, shooting off his face about Canadian literature.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 263" DBREF="64285">263</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></POLITICS></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>On <DATE VALUE="1964-12-20">December 20th, 1964</DATE>, <NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Wallace">Wallace</NAME> suffered his sixth and most critical heart attack. EW wrote to John Gray, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">he has been very much on the brink.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 274" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">274</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He was extremely slow to recover his strength.</P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Then on <DATE VALUE="1966-01-19">January 19, 1966</DATE>, EW suffered a stroke. She was left paralyzed on her left side and also experienced mental side effects including poor vision and grogginess. However, she gradually regained her eyesight and was able to read and also recovered the use of her left limbs.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 204-5" DBREF="64885">204-5</BIBCIT><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: the source mentions January, but not January 19th.</RESEARCHNOTE></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><FAMILY><MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND"><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="IMG"><DATE VALUE="1966-03-12">12 March 1966</DATE><CHRONPROSE>After another period of illness, <NAME>Wallace Wilson</NAME> died of a heart attack. This was a loss from which EW would never fully recover.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 274-5" DBREF="64285">274-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She was unable, both emotionally and physically, to attend his funeral service. The day after his death she wrote to John Gray: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">My darling died yesterday. How glad I would be to join him.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 274" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">274</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EW almost ceased altogether from correspondence this year. The letters that did appear reflect the enormous impact of Wallace&apos;s death on her life. She repeated her desire to join him.</P><P>She made an attempt to be brave, knowing it would have been Wallace&apos;s wish, but by the <DATE VALUE="1967-12-31" CERTAINTY="BY">end of 1967</DATE> her despair returned, compounded by her inability to write at this time.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 206-7" DBREF="64885">206-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></MEMBER></FAMILY></DIV1><DIV1><HEALTH ISSUE="MENTAL"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>Reading still offered EW considerable solace and she praised the travel writing of <NAME>Mary Kingsley</NAME> and <NAME>Simon Fraser</NAME>. However, her daily routine came to consist of exercises in physical therapy to continue to rehabilitate her limbs. Her letters reveal that she also experienced considerable memory loss, often repeating herself in letters to her friends. Visits from friends but more often relatives became the central moments in her life.</P><P>In <DATE VALUE="1972-05-">May of 1972</DATE>, one of her day nurses reported a decline in EW&apos;s mental health. She became unable to manage cheques and business transactions. At times, however, she was as sharp and witty as always. Doctors concluded she had likely suffered another stroke.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 279, 281" DBREF="64285">279, 281</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></HEALTH></DIV1><DIV1><LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED"><DIV2><SHORTPROSE><P>She was placed in institutional care, moved from her <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> apartment to the <ORGNAME>Arbutus Private Hospital</ORGNAME>, by her power of attorney in <DATE VALUE="1974-06-">June of 1974</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 282" DBREF="64285">282</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></LOCATION></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Death</HEADING><DEATH><DIV2><CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="SYS"><DATE>22 December 1980</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW died in a <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> private hospital after <CAUSE>kidney stone complications</CAUSE>, one month before her ninety-third birthday.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Stouck 283" DBREF="64285">283</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>A small service was held at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Christ Church Cathedral</PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> on <DATE VALUE="1980-12-27">December 27</DATE>. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 208" DBREF="64885">208</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></DIV2></DEATH></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE></SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></BIOGRAPHY>